---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import TracePlayer from "../../islands/TracePlayer.svelte";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import buggy from "../../../derived/elifladder/buggy.trace.json";
import procedural from "../../../derived/elifladder/procedural.trace.json";

// Buggy first: watch it fail in real state, then watch the fix.
const registers = [buggy, procedural];
---

<Base title="The elif ladder — GlassBox" description="First true branch wins. A loosest-first ladder grades a 95 as a D; order strictest-first.">
  <LessonNav slug="elifladder" position="top" />

  <h1>The elif ladder: order matters</h1>
  <p class="lede">An <code>if/elif</code> ladder stops at the first branch that's true and skips the rest. So the order of the tests <em>is</em> the logic — put the loosest band first and the strict ones become unreachable. Watch a 95 get the wrong grade.</p>

  <TracePlayer registers={registers} client:visible />

  <section class="explain card">
    <h2>What you are looking at</h2>
    <p>Watch <code>grade</code>, and which test the ladder stops at.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Buggy</strong> — The ladder tests <code>&gt;= 60</code> first. 95 passes it immediately, so <code>grade = 'D'</code> and the <code>&gt;= 90</code> branch is never reached.</li>
      <li><strong>Procedural</strong> — Reordered strictest-first, <code>&gt;= 90</code> is tested first, so a 95 correctly becomes <code>'A'</code>. A ladder must go narrowest-band-first.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="fineprint">Every state you see came from running the program under CPython's tracer at build time — see <a href="../../verification/">how GlassBox stays honest</a>.</p>
  </section>
  <LessonNav slug="elifladder" position="bottom" />
</Base>

<style>
  .explain { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
  .explain ul { margin: 0.6rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .explain li { margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .fineprint { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
